1/16/23, 9:17 AM - Deepu: Digital Images Representations


Deepu Kumar
Write about digital images and their representations.

Digital images are digital representations of visual information. They are composed of pixels, which are small, individual units of color. The pixels are arranged in a grid to create an image. Each pixel has a specific color value, which is typically represented using a color model such as RGB (red, green, blue) or CMYK (cyan, magenta, yellow, key).

Digital images can be stored in a variety of file formats, such as JPEG, PNG, and GIF. Each file format uses a specific method for compressing and storing the image data, which can affect the quality and size of the image. For example, JPEG uses lossy compression, which can result in a smaller file size but may also result in some loss of image quality. PNG uses lossless compression, which preserves all of the original image data but results in a larger file size.

In addition to these basic representations, digital images can also be represented using more complex data structures, such as vector graphics. Vector graphics use mathematical equations to define the shapes and colors in an image, rather than pixels. This allows for images that are infinitely scalable without loss of quality. Examples of vector image file formats include SVG and AI.

Digital images are used in a wide variety of applications, including photography, graphic design, and digital art. They are also used in many industries, such as advertising, marketing, and entertainment. With the increasing use of digital devices, the ability to create, edit, and share digital images has become a fundamental aspect of modern communication.
1/16/23, 9:19 AM - Deepu: Deepu Kumar
What are the different format commonly used for digital images? Name them and mention about their characteristic features.

There are several different image file formats commonly used for digital images, including:

JPEG (Joint Photographic Experts Group): This is one of the most widely used image file formats, and is known for its high compression rate, which makes it ideal for storing and sharing photographs and other images on the internet.

PNG (Portable Network Graphics): This is another popular image file format, and is known for its lossless compression, which means that no data is lost when the image is compressed. This makes it ideal for images with sharp lines and text, such as logos or graphics.

GIF (Graphics Interchange Format): This image file format is best known for its ability to create animated images. It uses lossless compression, and supports up to 256 colors.

TIFF (Tagged Image File Format): This format is widely used in the printing and publishing industry, and is known for its high-quality images. It supports lossless compression and a wide range of color depths.

BMP (Bitmap): This format is one of the oldest image file formats, and is native to the Windows operating system. It supports a wide range of color depths and is known for its high-quality images, but it has a large file size.

RAW: This format is used by digital cameras to store unprocessed image data. It is not a commonly used format for sharing images, but it is often used by photographers and professionals because it allows for greater flexibility in post-processing.

SVG(Scalable Vector Graphics): This format is not a raster image, it is a vector image format that is best suited for graphics, logos, icons, and illustrations. It is resolution-independent, which means it can be scaled to any size without losing quality.
